## Step 9 – Prepare Data for Normalization

Remove analytical blanks and retain only biological samples and QCs.

```r
analysis_ids <- c(sample_ids, qc_ids)

meta_analysis <- meta %>%
  filter(filename %in% analysis_ids) %>%
  arrange(match(filename, analysis_ids))

mat_before <- mat_filt[
  ,
  analysis_ids,
  drop = FALSE
]
```

---

## Step 10 – Missing Value Imputation

### Purpose

Allow log transformation and multivariate analyses.

### Procedure

Missing values are replaced by half of the minimum positive value observed for each feature.

```r
impute_halfmin <- function(x) {

  min_pos <- suppressWarnings(
    min(x[x > 0], na.rm = TRUE)
  )

  if (!is.finite(min_pos))
    min_pos <- 1

  x[is.na(x)] <- min_pos / 2

  x
}
```

Apply the function across all features.

### Note

Half-min imputation is used here as a simple exploratory strategy and may be replaced by alternative methods depending on study objectives.

---

## Step 11 – Total Signal Normalization

### Purpose

Reduce global intensity differences among samples.

### Procedure

Normalize each sample by its total signal.

```r
mat_norm_linear <- sweep(
  mat_before_imp,
  2,
  colSums(mat_before_imp),
  FUN = "/"
)
```

---

## Step 12 – Log Transformation

Apply log transformation:

```r
mat_norm <- log10(
  mat_norm_linear + 1e-6
)
```

### Purpose

* reduce skewness;
* reduce heteroscedasticity;
* decrease the influence of extreme values;
* improve multivariate modeling.

---

## Step 13 – Evaluate Total Signal Before and After Normalization

Compare the total signal distribution before and after normalization.

Generate boxplots separated by sample type.

Expected outcome:

* reduced signal variability;
* comparable signal scale among samples;
* improved consistency between biological samples and QCs.

---

## Step 14 – PCA Before Normalization

Perform PCA using the imputed matrix.

```r
pca_before <- prcomp(
  t(log10(mat_before_imp + 1)),
  scale. = TRUE
)
```

### Purpose

* identify outliers;
* assess QC clustering;
* inspect analytical variability;
* evaluate baseline data structure.

---

## Step 15 – PCA After Normalization

Perform PCA using the normalized matrix.

```r
pca_after <- prcomp(
  t(mat_norm),
  scale. = TRUE
)
```

### Purpose

* verify preservation of biological structure;
* assess improvement in QC clustering;
* confirm reduction of technical variability.

